00:00:12.450 --> 00:00:17.220
Also, please like and leave a comment, and
share the video to help spread this free series

00:00:17.220 --> 00:00:18.980
of videos.

00:00:18.980 --> 00:00:20.130
Thanks for your help.

00:00:20.130 --> 00:00:22.720
Let’s get started.

00:00:22.720 --> 00:00:26.640
In this lab you will use what you learned
in Day 2’s lecture video to connect these

00:00:26.640 --> 00:00:29.439
network devices together.

00:00:29.439 --> 00:00:33.040
You can select various types of connections
from the bottom left here.

00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:40.740
We’ll be using copper straight-through,
copper cross-over, and fiber connections.

00:00:40.740 --> 00:00:46.219
Note that packet tracer doesn’t differentiate
between single-mode and multimode fiber, but

00:00:46.219 --> 00:00:50.950
try to think about which type would be appropriate
when you use a fiber connection.

00:00:50.950 --> 00:00:54.370
So, I’ll start here in the bottom left.

00:00:54.370 --> 00:00:59.940
First, the connection between SW3 and PC1.

00:00:59.940 --> 00:01:05.300
For the purpose of this lab, we’re assuming
that Auto MDI-X is disabled or not supported

00:01:05.300 --> 00:01:10.150
on the devices, so we have to think about
whether to use a straight-through or cross-over

00:01:10.150 --> 00:01:12.640
copper cable.

00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:19.970
PCs transmit data on pins 1 and 2, and receive
data on pins 3 and 6.

00:01:19.970 --> 00:01:26.320
Switches are the opposite, they transmit data
on pins 3 and 6 and receive data on pins 1

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:27.750
and 2.

00:01:27.750 --> 00:01:33.640
So, we can use a straight-through cable to
connect all of these PCs, as well as SRV1,

00:01:33.640 --> 00:01:35.930
to the switches.

00:01:35.930 --> 00:01:41.690
Select straight-through cable here, and connect
the PCs to their appropriate switch.

00:01:41.690 --> 00:01:49.570
PC1 to SW3..connect the fastethernet0 interface
on the PC, which is the PC’s network interface

00:01:49.570 --> 00:01:53.970
card, to any of the fastethernet interfaces
on the switch.

00:01:53.970 --> 00:02:06.560
Next is PC2 to SW4...PC3 to SW7...and SRV1 to SW8.

00:02:06.560 --> 00:02:10.080
Now we’ve got a bunch of switches to connect
together.

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:14.590
Devices of the same type require crossover
cables, or else the transmit pins will be

00:02:14.590 --> 00:02:20.450
connected to the transmit pins, and the receive
pins will be connected to the receive pins,

00:02:20.450 --> 00:02:23.700
which will not allow data to be sent successfully between the devices.

00:02:23.700 --> 00:02:39.970
So, let’s connect these switches, SW3 to
SW1...SW1 to SW2...SW4 to SW2...SW7 to SW5...

00:02:39.970 --> 00:02:51.240
SW5 to SW6...and last SW8 to SW6.

00:02:51.240 --> 00:02:54.590
Next let’s connect these switches to the
routers.

00:02:54.590 --> 00:03:02.090
Routers are like PCs, they transmit on pins
1 and 2 and receive on pins 3 and 6.

00:03:02.090 --> 00:03:05.990
So let’s connect them to the switches with
straight-through cables.

00:03:05.990 --> 00:03:20.400
SW1 to R2...SW2 to R2...SW5 to R4...and SW6 to
R4.

00:03:20.400 --> 00:03:24.830
Now it’s time to connect the routers.

00:03:24.830 --> 00:03:31.120
Since they are the same device type, we need
to use crossover cables if we use copper cabling.

00:03:31.120 --> 00:03:34.430
Take care to look at the distances here.

00:03:34.430 --> 00:03:41.400
Since R1 and R2 are just 50 meters apart,
we can use copper cabling, which permits distances

00:03:41.400 --> 00:03:43.849
up to 100 meters.

00:03:43.849 --> 00:03:53.790
So I’ll connect R2 to R1 with a crossover
cable.  R1 and R3 are 3 kilometers apart,

00:03:53.790 --> 00:03:58.280
so clearly we will have to use a fiber-optic
connection here.

00:03:58.280 --> 00:04:02.819
Although packet tracer doesnt differentiate
between single-mode and multimode, which is

00:04:02.819 --> 00:04:03.960
appropriate here?

00:04:03.960 --> 00:04:11.069
Well, mutli mode fiber allows distances up
to 550 meters, which is more than UTP, but

00:04:11.069 --> 00:04:14.180
not enough for this connection.

00:04:14.180 --> 00:04:19.980
Single-mode allows much longer distances,
30 kilometers, 40 kilometers, even more, so

00:04:19.980 --> 00:04:23.099
in this case we would use single-mode fiber.

00:04:23.099 --> 00:04:29.150
Let’s connect them, note that this symbol
here is used for fiber optic connections in

00:04:29.150 --> 00:04:35.370
packet tracer, notice the two spaces, for
both the transmit and receive cables.

00:04:35.370 --> 00:04:41.029
Finally, R3 and R4 are separated by 250 meters.

00:04:41.029 --> 00:04:47.189
That’s too long for a UTP cable, but also
not so long that we need single-mode fiber.

00:04:47.189 --> 00:04:50.150
A multimode fiber cable would be sufficient.

00:04:50.150 --> 00:04:56.289
Let’s connect them together...Okay, the
devices are now all connected.

00:04:56.289 --> 00:05:00.460
That’s all for this lab.

